We compare our findings \eqref{eq:scal1} with the bosonization approach, particularly with  Ref.\  \cite{Teo2009}, where the   
the  scaling exponent \eqref{eq:scal0} of the conductance in the weak backscattering limit was found. 
The exponent in this case can be regarded as  twice the scaling dimension of the tunneling operator at the edge state,  $(K-1)^{2}/2K$.  In the considered setup one TI is substituted by the semi-infinite spinful wire. The contact between a semi-infinite quantum wire and a 3D metal  was analyzed in \cite{Fabrizio1995}, with the  conductance scaling exponent  found as $\frac12 (K_\rho^{-1}+K_\sigma^{-1})-1$. For spin isotropic interaction in our case we should put $K_\sigma=1$ and  $K_\rho=K_2$. Combining both cases we obtain the overall scaling exponent in the form $(K_1+1/K_1)/2+(1+1/K_2)/2-2$ which expression exactly corresponds to Eq. \eqref{eq:scal1}. 



Summarizing here, we obtained the phase portrait for the case of the tunneling from the spinful wire tip to the helical edge state, we find the scaling exponents which are in agreement with bosonization approach when available. 
We note that the appearance of the RG fixed lines in the plane of available conductances  is rather unusual phenomenon, discussed previously in the case of  chiral Y-junction for certain relations between the interaction parameters. \cite{Aristov2012a} 



\section{Conclusions} 
In this paper we first considered a four-terminal junction of  helical edge states of topological insulators.  The time reversal symmetry arguments defines the general structure of single-particle S-matrix, describing the tunneling processes between the edges. We employ the previously developed approach to the renormalization of the conductance matrix within the fermionic formalism. Making partial summation of the perturbation theory series in interaction of Tomonaga-Luttinger type, we find a set non-perturbative RG equations for the conductances.  These equations are solved and the results agree with the bosonization studies, when available. We generalize our approach to the asymmetric situation when the corner junction is between two helical edge states characterized by different interaction strength.  The fixed point structure, scaling exponents and the overall phase portrait of this setup is obtained. 

Finally, we observe that the considered form of S-matrix can be equally applied to the description of the tunneling from the tip of spinful wire to the helical edge state. The difference from the above cases is in the form of interaction. We apply duly modified approach to address this setup and also find the set of RG equation for the conductances. The phase portrait is now more involved and, depending on the interaction,  we find the possibility for the lines of fixed points to appear, in addition to conventional fixed points. Where available, our results for scaling exponents agree with  expressions obtained in bosonization.  



